<br>
Earth is the tanking pet, has lots of hitpoints and decent damage.  It is the usually the solo pet of choice for non-epicked mages because it casts root.   Some mages, like myself, solo by chain-casting earth, relying on a rooted enemy to provide the time to cast another pet.  Earth pets are highly resistant to disease based attacks.<br>
<br>
Fire pet has a built in damage shield that is stronger than anything the magician can cast.  It is also a solo tank pet for the obvious reason.  Some mages prefer to solo with this pet to take advantage of the damage shield, and this is a good choice when the enemy strikes quickly and has relatively low hitpoints.  Can also be useful against multiple green mobs.  Without root, aggro management becomes more important.  Post-50 Fire pets act like NPC wizards, and mages have a mixed, mostly negative view of them, but pre-50 they rock, especially in the Old World.  They have a fire proc, and generally are immune to fire.<br>
<br>
Air stuns, which is useful against casters and hard hitting mobs.  One of the two standard pets to use in groups.  It deals adequate damage, but is not that good a tank.  Air pets are highly resistant to cold attacks, and may be immune to lifetaps <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (which might be a bug)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Water pets pre-50 are the most well rounded pets in terms of tankability and damage dealing.  Post-50 water pets are backstabbing rogues with relatively fewer hitpoints, and are our damage specialty pets.  Under ideal conditions they do nearly as much damage as epic pets.  Water pets have a damage proc, and are highly resistant to poison attacks.  They are the other group elemental.<br>
<br>
The Epic pet combines almost all the best features of all the elementals.  It has a better damage shield than the fire, stuns like the air, has more hitpoints than earth, and has a stronger proc than water.  It is slow to cast and recast this elemental.  The quest is possibly the hardest epic quest, but it increases the personal power of its owner more than any other epic.  At level 60 with 80 AA I still lack the epic, despite repeated trips to Hate.  A very small minority of mages have their epic, and it is a point of pride for its owner.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yikitiki:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  maybe the Earth elemental scale is not such a bad idea.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Cyricus</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in another thread suggested a straight air elemental as a model for the warder.  This might be a very good model for comparison purposes, and I am pretty sure would not generate a heated reaction.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yikitiki:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Also, the proc thing is kind of a mystery to us unfortunately. You don't see the numbers saying when it hits, or when it gets resisted, or how much it hits for. I think we would all feel more comfortable w/ some numbers to back up the damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Uhm yeppers!  Us too.  It does hide a lot of damage, making things much harder to evaluate.  But since it works against resistance, not AC, it gives you an another avenue for dealing damage.  Just how much is proper, I have no idea.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Tarqal:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Mages do not nuke<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Something of an overstatement.  Circumstances dictate what strategy is best, and often nuking is the best policy.  Nukes are fast with absolute control over the target.  However, relying on pets for more damage makes much better use of mana.  Nukes make better use of time.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yikitiki:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  phantom armor = ac<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Useful mostly at lower levels, and in groups with a priest where the pet tanks.  I can summon up over 100 AC and 100 HP worth of gear, but this is not that much.  However, when a pet has additional priest buffs, the additional AC and HP makes more difference, as it helps to close the gap between the pet's AC and the mob's ATK.  Also, it cannot be dispelled.  However, given the ease of reclaiming and recasting a pet, summoned armor is only useful under certain circumstances.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yikiti:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  summoned staves = melee/dps.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Summoned weapons are nearly worthless, except for other people's pets.  They do not add to damage, except for the Sword of Runes against summoned mobs, which are rare, and the proc hardly ever occurs.  More common is to give the elemental a pair of gnoll hide lariats which proc stun, and richer mages might even give a pair of Yakeshas.  Of course these weapons cannot be recovered.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yikiti:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  do you have stuff that makes them cast spells, procs, upgrades any of the above?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Nopers.  A summoned pet-only weapon that procs has been a desire of many mages for a long time.  Besides the 15% haste muzzle, the summoned armor, and purchased weapons with procs, that is it.<br>
<br>
I think it is pretty clear that it is beastlord's job to cast buffs that modify their pets and add features.  I see little in the way of new mage pet buffs in the future, with the possible exception of an anti-charm buff, or a non-dispellable version of our anti-fear buff.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Darkov:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I'm confused. On one hand, some mages are saying Warder DPS should be increased to a similiar level of an Earth Elemental, on the other hand they are saying they should have less hp/tanking ability, and on the other hand are saying beastlords lack the DPS as a class.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Some mages, so far, is me.<br>
<br>
Here is my reasoning.  If you surrender to the primitive yet understandable urge to demand a warder that is a major DPS machine, then many mages will feel threatened and will be up in arms.  Like it or not, agree or not, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> does appear to take that into account when new spells are proposed that intrude on the perogatives of another class.<br>
<br>
So I says to myself, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Self, how can increased DPS for warders been presented in such a way that as many mages as possible will just nod and say okay?&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  So I analyze things in terms of damage dealing and tankability, and try to come up with some suggestions.<br>
<br>
For example, I think almost no mage would blink if warders were equivalent to air pets with different skins, as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Cyricus</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> suggested.<br>
<br>
I know two things however that will make many mages angry.  First, the epic pet is a damage machine and the pride of the class.  It is a very hard epic, and few mages have it.  If an ordinary pet is seen as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;better&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than the epic, then many mages are going to simply drop a load right there on the carpet, regardless of whether they themselves have the epic.<br>
<br>
Second, for the vast majority of non-epicked mages, the 50+ water elementals are our specialty damage pets.  For similar reasons, if this threshold is surpassed, many mages will be upset, especially if it requires no special positioning for the warder.  So I consider this to be the upper limit before mages squeak.<br>
<br>
So then the idea becomes, how to sell a higher but possibly adequate bottom limit to mages, one where opposition would be minimized.  As Air is a specialty stun pet, I think <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Cyricus</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is right to propose that as a model.<br>
<br>
However, in melee, there is this traditional balance in melee classes between tankability and damage dealing.  In theory, better tanks deal less damage, and better damage dealer tank less well <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (with the notable exception of monks)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
Suppose warders were upgraded to do a bit more damage in melee than earth elementals.  Some DPS.  Mage whiner starts posting that the sky is falling and mages are doomed.  A more thoughtful mage points out that since warders are worse tanks than an earth elemental, it is only fair that warders deal more damage.  Thoughtful mage also points out that beastlords deal damage almost exclusively through their warder.  Whiner mages are kept to a minimum, while consensus is built around thoughtful mage.<br>
<br>
So even if might ultimately be fair that warder DPS be even higher than that, if you pass either of the two mage pain thresholds I mentioned earlier, many otherwise thoughtful mages will react viscerally, effectively becoming whiner mages.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Yikiti:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Raz had said we are weak on the DPS scale because, the way I understand it, he feels that we as Beastlords should be getting more DPS, not our pet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Actually, I think you need upgrades on <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>both</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> warder and lord DPS.  However, warders are on the table <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>now</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, so that is properly the current emphasis of beastlords.  Upgrading beastlord melee DPS is a much trickier issue, and will take longer to solve, as it involves skills, combat tables, and gear.<br>
<br>
What I don't think is a good idea is to have lords remain weak.  The stronger the warder is made, the less balanced stronger lords are.  What I am suggesting is to get a good chunk now, the best deal you can without setting off all the mage and necro car alarms, and then work on lord melee.  Then you will be much closer to balanced.  At that point, it will be much more clear exactly where beastlords are, and what they still lack, and a more rational discussion can take place of what remains to be done and why.<br>
<br>
I like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Raimundo</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s perspective, as it is close to how I see things ought to be.  Strong lord, strong warder.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Sage ArchMage Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
